---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout
    title="LSCSS FAQ"
    description="Frequently asked questions about Layered Semantic CSS."
>
    <section class="site-hero">
        <p class="eyebrow">FAQ</p>

        <h1>
            Frequently asked questions
        </h1>

        <p class="intro">
            The questions people usually ask before adopting a CSS system, or
            after inheriting one held together by hope and important declarations.
        </p>
    </section>

    <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="FAQ sections">
        <a href="#utilities">Utilities</a>
        <a href="#bem">BEM</a>
        <a href="#frameworks">Frameworks</a>
        <a href="#scope">@scope</a>
        <a href="#legacy">Legacy CSS</a>
        <a href="#files">File size</a>
    </nav>

    <section id="utilities" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Is LSCSS anti-utility?
        </h2>

        <p>
            No. It is anti-unnecessary utility chains pretending to be
            architecture. Utilities are useful for accessibility helpers and
            genuinely universal patterns such as <code>.vh</code> and
            <code>.a11y-link</code>.
        </p>

        <p>
            If the same utility group keeps appearing together, it should
            probably become a named component.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="bem" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Does LSCSS replace BEM?
        </h2>

        <p>
            It borrows useful parts of BEM, especially explicit modifiers, but
            removes much of the naming ceremony. Short scoped child selectors,
            layers, and state classes reduce the need for long
            <code>block__element--modifier</code> chains.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="frameworks" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Does this work with frameworks?
        </h2>

        <p>
            Yes. LSCSS is CSS architecture, not a framework choice. It works
            with Astro, React, Vue, Svelte, Eleventy, server-rendered sites,
            and large legacy systems that still have emotional ties to jQuery.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="scope" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Does @scope replace LSCSS?
        </h2>

        <p>
            No. <code>@scope</code> improves selector boundaries and reduces
            naming ceremony. It does not replace layers, modifiers, state
            rules, theme ownership, tokens, or hack management.
        </p>

        <p>
            <code>@scope</code> is a feature. LSCSS is the wider methodology.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="legacy" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            What about old projects and legacy CSS?
        </h2>

        <p>
            Do not rewrite everything for sport. Start by adding layers,
            isolate old CSS in the legacy layer, and improve active components
            as you touch them. Migration should be controlled, not theatrical.
        </p>
    </section>

    <section id="files" class="content-block">
        <h2>
            Should CSS files have a strict line limit?
        </h2>

        <p>
            No fixed number solves maintainability. The real rule is simple:
            if a file feels too large to understand quickly, review it.
        </p>

        <p>
            Around 300 to 400 lines is often the point where hidden
            sub-components, repeated patterns, or old hacks start asking for
            attention.
        </p>
    </section>
</DocsLayout>
